    "## 2. Theoretical Background\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2.1 Vectors and Arrays\n",
    "\n",
    "In mathematics, a **vector** is a quantity having direction as well as magnitude. In computing, we represent vectors as 1D arrays.\n",
    "\n",
    "A vector $\mathbf{v}$ with $n$ components:\n",
    "\\[\n",
    "\\mathbf{v} = \\begin{bmatrix} v_1 & v_2 & \\cdots & v_n \\end{bmatrix}
",
    "\\]\n",
    "\n",
    "In NumPy:\n",
    "```python\n",
    "v = np.array([v1, v2, ..., vn])\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2.2 Element-wise Operations\n",
    "\n",
    "When we apply operations to arrays, NumPy performs them element by element:\n",
    "\n",
    "Given arrays $\mathbf{a}$ and $\mathbf{b}$ of the same shape:\n",
    "\\[\n",
    "\\mathbf{a} + \\mathbf{b} = \\begin{bmatrix} a_1 + b_1 & a_2 + b_2 & \\cdots & a_n + b_n \\end{bmatrix}
",
    "\\]\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2.3 Broadcasting\n",
    "\n",
    "**Broadcasting** allows NumPy to work with arrays of different shapes during arithmetic operations. The smaller array is "broadcast" across the larger array so they have compatible shapes.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Rules:**\n",
    "1. If arrays have different dimensions, prepend 1s to the shape of the smaller array\n",
    "2. Arrays are compatible if, for each dimension, either:\n",
    "   - The sizes are equal, or\n",
    "   - One of them is 1\n",
    "\n",
    "**Example:** Adding a scalar to a matrix\n",
    "\\[\n",
    "\\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 2 \\\\ 3 & 4 \\end{bmatrix} + 10 = \\begin{bmatrix} 11 & 12 \\\\ 13 & 14 \\end{bmatrix}
",
    "\\]\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2.4 Image Representation\n",
    "\n",
    "A grayscale image with height $H$ and width $W$ is represented as a matrix $\mathbf{I} \\in \\mathbb{R}^{H \\times W}$ where each element $I_{i,j} \\in [0, 255]$ represents pixel intensity.\n",
    "\n",
    "- 0 = Black\n",
    "- 255 = White\n",
    "- Values in between = Shades of gray"
   ]
  },
